# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1915-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] 1903 was the third year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the still-new American League.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in fifth place with a record or 65–71 (.478), 25 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The 1903 Tigers outscored their opponents 567 to 539.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 224,523, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] 1904 was the fourth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 62–90 (.408), 32 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] They played ten tie games, which is the major league record.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The 1904 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 627 to 505.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 177,796, seventh out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] In the year before Ty Cobb's arrival, pitcher George Mullin had a higher batting average than any of the team's regulars at .290.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] 1905 was the fifth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in third place with a record of 79–74 (.516), 151⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers posted a run differential of -97, the lowest ever by a team with a winning record, breaking the previous record of -81 held by the 1882 Detroit Wolverines; the Tigers lost 48 games by 3 or more runs.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 602 to 512, the largest negative run differential ever for a Major League team with a winning record.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 193,384, eighth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] The **1915 Detroit Tigers** won a club-record 100 games and narrowly lost the American League pennant to the Boston Red Sox, who won 101 games.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Though four other Tigers teams have won 100 games (1934, 1961, 1968, and 1984), only the 1934 Tigers had a better winning percentage.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] The 1915 Detroit Tigers team is remembered for its all-star outfield of Ty Cobb, Sam Crawford, and Bobby Veach—who finished #1, #2, and #3 in the American League in both runs batted in and total bases.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Baseball historian Bill James ranks the Tigers' 1915 outfield as the best in major league history.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Catcher **Oscar Stanage** was a weak hitter but one of the best defensive catchers of the deadball era.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In thirteen seasons with the Tigers, Stanage caught 1,074 games – second only to Bill Freehan in team history.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Known for his strong throwing arm, Stanage threw out more baserunners than any other catcher in the 1910s.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Stanage still holds the American League record for most assists by a catcher, with 212 in 1911, and his career average of 1.29 assists per game is the fifth best in major league history.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Stanage was not as skilled with the glove; his 41 errors in 1911 were the most by a catcher in the 20th Century.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman **"Tioga George" Burns** played for the Tigers from 1914 to 1917.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1915, Burns hit only .243 with 18 doubles.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Burns went on to become a star after leaving the Tigers.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1926, he was named the American League's MVP with a .358 batting average and an all-time MLB record 64 doubles.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Second baseman **Ralph Young** played for the Tigers from 1915 to 1921.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1915, Young had a .243 batting average, but a much more respectable .339 on-base percentage.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] At 5'5", Young was one of the shortest players ever to play in a Tigers uniform.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] His small stature, and correspondingly small strike zone, assisted him in both collecting walks and avoiding strikeouts.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In nine seasons, Young collected 495 bases on balls and struck out only 254 times (in 3,643 at bats).
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Young led all American League second basemen with 32 errors in 1915.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Donie Bush** was Detroit's starting shortstop for thirteen seasons from 1909 to 1921.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1914, Bush had 425 putouts (still the major league record for shortstops) and 969 chances (still the American League record).
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] He led the American League in assists by a shortstop in 1915 with 504.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] During the decade from 1910 to 1919, no one had more bases on balls than Bush.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Bush also ranked among the league leaders in stolen bases nine times, including in 1915 when he stole 35 bases.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] With his ability to get on base, and having Cobb and Crawford batting behind him, Bush was also among the league leaders in runs scored ten times, including his 1915 total of 99 runs.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Third baseman **Ossie Vitt** played seven seasons with the Tigers and was a poor hitter but a good fielder.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] He led all American League third basemen in 1915 and 1916 in putouts, assists and fielding percentage.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] His 208 assists in 1916 have not been exceeded by a Detroit third baseman since that time.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] While not a good hitter for average, Vitt was a good contact hitter and one of the best bunters of the era.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] He led the American League with 42 sacrifice hits in 1915, and his career total of 259 sacrifice hits (in a relatively short career) ranks 32nd best in major league history.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Vitt was also one of the toughest players to strike out in MLB history.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] For his career, he struck out an average of once every 26.6 at bats, 35th best in MLB history.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers' 1915 outfield, with Bobby Veach in left, Ty Cobb in center, and Sam Crawford in right, has been ranked by baseball historian Bill James as the greatest outfield of all time.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Though the league batting average in 1915 was .248, Cobb hit .369 with 99 RBIs and 144 runs scored, Crawford hit .313 and drove in 112 runs, and Veach hit .299 with 112 RBIs.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] The three Detroit outfielders ranked #1, #2, and #3 in total bases and RBIs.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Cobb also set a major league record with 96 stolen bases in 1915, a record which would not be broken for nearly 50 years until Maury Wills stole 104 bases in 1962.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Pitcher Hooks Dauss played his entire fifteen-year career with the Tigers and is the team's all-time win leader.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1915, Dauss won 24 games (2nd most in the American League) and lost 13, ending up with a 2.50 ERA in 309+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Dauss was also an excellent fielding pitcher.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] His career range factor of 2.28 is 65 points higher than the average pitcher of his era.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] He had 1128 assists in his career, including an American League leading 137 in 1915.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] His career fielding percentage of .968 was also 20 points higher than the average pitcher of his era.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Pitcher Harry Coveleski joined the Tigers in 1914.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] He was a 20-game winner in his first three seasons in Detroit (1914–1916).
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1915, he had a record of 22–13 with an ERA of 2.45, and he followed in 1916 with a 1.97 ERA.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In four of his five seasons with the Tigers, Coveleski's ERA was under three, and his 2.34 ERA with the Tigers is still the franchise's all-time career record.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Pitcher Jean Dubuc was a pitching phenom at Notre Dame before entering professional baseball.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1915, he went 17–12 for the Tigers with a 3.21 ERA.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] He is most remembered for his role in the 1918 Chicago Black Sox scandal.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Pitcher Rube Benton testified that he had seen a telegram addressed to Dubuc, from Sleepy Bill Burns advising Dubuc: "Bet on the Cincinnati team today." After being linked to the scandal, Dubuc went to Canada and continued to play minor league ball.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Dubuc is also credited with having signed Hank Greenberg while serving as a major league scout for the Tigers.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Bernie Boland was an early relief specialist who made his major league debut in 1915.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Boland was 13–7 with a 3.11 ERA in his rookie season and came within one batter of throwing a perfect game.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] On August 16, 1915, Boland retired the first 26 Cleveland Indians batters he faced, only to give up a hit to Ben Paschal.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Ironically, Paschal's hit off Boland was his only hit of the 1915 season.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Boland and the Tigers went on to win the game 3–1.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] In 1926, Boland returned to the news for comments he made concerning a game-fixing scandal involving Ty Cobb.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Boland, then a paving contractor in Detroit, was the Tigers pitcher in a 1919 game against Cleveland that Cobb had reportedly agreed to fix.
[src:1915-detroit-tigers-season/1915-detroit-tigers-season] Boland told the Detroit News in 1926 that he figured "about one in every 300 games is crooked," and he was glad that "some of them are getting justice at last".
